.TH ASRFACET-RB 1 "April 2026" "ASRFacet-Rb 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
asrfacet-rb \- authorized attack surface reconnaissance and security mapping framework
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B asrfacet-rb
<command> [arguments] [options]
.br
.B asrfacet-rb
--console
.br
.B asrfacet-rb
manual [section]
.SH DESCRIPTION
ASRFacet-Rb is a Ruby 3.2+ framework for authorized attack surface reconnaissance.
It combines passive discovery, recursive DNS and certificate enrichment, service mapping,
HTTP probing, crawling, JavaScript endpoint mining, asset scoring, monitoring, and
lightweight finding generation.
.PP
The framework is intended only for systems you own or have explicit written permission
to test. Scope control, recon memory, and educational self-documentation are built in.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B scan DOMAIN
Run the full reconnaissance pipeline.
.TP
.B passive DOMAIN
Run passive discovery only.
.TP
.B ports HOST
Run a focused TCP port scan.
.TP
.B dns DOMAIN
Collect DNS records only.
.TP
.B console
Launch the framework console.
.TP
.B interactive
Launch the standalone guided workflow.
.TP
.B help [topic], explain TOPIC, manual [section]
Show built-in documentation.
.SH CONSOLE
The console is the richest operator interface and supports framework-style commands such as:
.IP
show commands
.br
show options
.br
show workflow
.br
show config
.br
show learning
.br
info recon
.br
man
.br
wizard
.PP
Normal framework commands can also be run directly inside the console.
.SH WIZARD
The console-only wizard asks what you are trying to achieve, how careful you want to be,
what format you want, and whether monitoring or memory should be enabled.
It then recommends a concrete command and can execute it for you.
.SH RECON BASICS
Passive reconnaissance uses third-party data without touching the target.
Active reconnaissance confirms assets by making requests or opening connections.
Effective attack surface mapping combines both approaches, then ranks the results so
deeper testing focuses on the most valuable assets first.
.SH CONFIGURATION
Project defaults are stored in
.I config/default.yml
and user overrides are stored in
.I ~/.asrfacet_rb/config.yml .
Common settings include timeouts, thread counts, wordlists, output preferences, and HTTP behavior.
.SH OUTPUTS
.TP
.B cli
Terminal-friendly tables and summaries.
.TP
.B json
Machine-readable output.
.TP
.B html
Offline report with findings, graph relationships, and top targets.
.TP
.B txt
Plain-text export.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I bin/asrfacet-rb
Primary executable.
.TP
.I config/default.yml
Project defaults.
.TP
.I ~/.asrfacet_rb/config.yml
User configuration overrides.
.TP
.I ~/.asrfacet_rb/memory/
Per-target scan memory.
.TP
.I man/asrfacet-rb.1
Manual page source.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B asrfacet-rb scan example.com --format html --output report.html
Run a full scan and save an HTML report.
.TP
.B asrfacet-rb passive example.com --format json --output passive.json
Run passive discovery only and save JSON output.
.TP
.B asrfacet-rb --console
Open the framework console.
.SH SAFETY
Only use ASRFacet-Rb on systems you own or have explicit written permission to test.
Use scope controls and exclusions to keep the target boundary explicit.
.SH SEE ALSO
.B asrfacet-rb manual
